<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Thu 26 Apr 2007
Source: St. Helena Star [edited]
<http://www.sthelenastar.com/articles/2007/04/26/news/local/doc462ff3bd97a71971867807.txt>

At least 3 cases of _E. coli_ [O157] have been traced to tainted meat
at a St. Helena Little League snack shack. In addition to 3 confirmed
cases, 2 other children exhibited the same symptoms for the same
length of time, and shared the Little League snack shack link, but
were not positively diagnosed for technical reasons, said Napa County
Public Health Officer Karen Smith. The 5 children, all St. Helena
Little League participants and 2 of them siblings, have since fully
recovered. One of them was hospitalized for a short time.
After it became clear that the 1st case, reported on 3 Apr 2007, was
not an isolated incident, county officials gathered the sick
children's recent food histories and found that they had all eaten
hamburger products at Little League snack shacks in St. Helena and
Calistoga, Smith said.
Meat samples from the Calistoga snack shack came back negative, but
St. Helena's tested positive for _E. coli_. Meat from the same lot at
Salami Lady's Cash and Carry, the Napa store that supplied St.
Helena's snack shack, also tested positive, Smith said.
The small outbreak has prompted the Merced-based Richwood Meat Co. to
recall about 100 000 pounds of beef.
[Byline: Jesse Duarte]
